The best approach is **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface behind mockable interfaces. No need to write custom wrappers.

**1. Install the packages:**
```
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

**2. Register in DI** (`Program.cs` / `Startup.cs`):
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem`** instead of calling statics:
```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));

manager.Save("/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/out.txt"));

Assert.False(manager.EnsureDirectory("/nope"));
```

**Why this over custom wrappers?** `System.IO.Abstractions` covers `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `FileInfo`, etc. in one package, includes `MockFileSystem` for tests, and is widely adopted — no need to maintain your own interface surface.

Once the packages are installed, use constructor injection to replace each static call site with `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*`. If you want help **bulk-migrating** the call sites across your project, I can do that too — just say the word.
